<div class="markdown"><h1>Poisson approximation to Binomial</h1>
<p>This notebook explores using the Poissson approximation to the Binomial. This can be useful for a number of reasons:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>The Binomial probability mass formula becomes more unwieldy for large <span class="tex">$N$</span> faster than it does for the Poisson.</p>
</li>
<li><p>In actuarial, and other contexts, <span class="tex">$N$</span> can be a non-integer value &#40;think partial period exposures&#41; and rounding up or down could materially distort the posterior estimate if <span class="tex">$N$</span> is small.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>We will look at the approximation across a range of parameters <span class="tex">$q$</span> &#40;the probabilty a binomial event occurs&#41; and <span class="tex">$N$</span> &#40;the number of chances for the event to occur, or &quot;exposures&quot;&#41;. </p>
<p>Under certain conditions, the Poisson distribution can approximate the Binomial, where the average number of events, <span class="tex">$λ&#61;N*q$</span>.</p>
<p>What are those conditions? <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution#Poisson_approximation">According to Wikipedia</a>: </p>
<blockquote>
<p>According to two rules of thumb, this approximation is good if n ≥ 20 and p ≤ 0.05, or if n ≥ 100 and np ≤ 10.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It&#39;s not really that simple, and arguably a bit restrictive as this notebook will show.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Approach</h2>
<p>We will use Julia and Turing.jl to simulate the posterior distribution. Our prior for the parameter <span class="tex">$q$</span> will be <span class="tex">$&#123;Uniform&#125; &#61; Beta&#40;1,1&#41;$</span>.</p>
<p>We will sample from the posterior using the No-U-Turn &#40;NUTS&#41; sampler, and aggregate the results of the chains over 30 trials of simulated outcomes for the given <span class="tex">$q$</span> and <span class="tex">$N$</span>.</p>
<p>This is overkill for a toy problem where we could just model the parameters themselves, but it demonstrates using Bayesian MCMC techniques in a simple, exploratory fashion.</p>
<p>We begin by importing the relevant packages:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>begin
    using Turing
    using CairoMakie
    using StatsBase
    using MCMCChains
    using DataFrames
    using ThreadsX
    using Logging
    using Markdown
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h2>Define the Models</h2>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@model function poisson(N,n_events) 
    q ~ Beta(1,1)
    
    n_events ~ Poisson(q*N)
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-poisson' class='pluto-output'>poisson (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@model function binom(N,n_events) 
    q ~ Beta(1,1)
    
    n_events ~ Binomial(N,q)
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-binom' class='pluto-output'>binom (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Sample from the Posterior</h2>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>Logging.disable_logging(Logging.Warn); #Disable warning logs to improve sampling time</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>This is a collection of samples &#40;chains&#41; from Markov chains that are sampled in proportion to the posterior density. If this is new to you, I highly recommend the book <em>Statistical Rethinking</em>:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@time bpchains = map(model_points) do mp
    
    ThreadsX.map(1:trials) do i
        claims = sum(rand() &lt; mp.q for _ in 1:mp.N)
        bc = sample(binom(mp.N,claims), NUTS(), 500)
        pc = sample(poisson(mp.N,claims), NUTS(), 500)

        (;bc,pc)
    end
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Results</h2>
<p>The results indicate that the Poisson is a good fit when <span class="tex">$q$</span> is small, where &quot;small&quot; depends on N, but in general it seems to provide a good fit in less restrictive cases than the &quot;rule of thumb&quot; quoted below. E.g. go ahead and use the Poisson approximation when you&#39;ve got enough expsoures even if <span class="tex">$q$</span> is well above <span class="tex">$0.10$</span>. The Poisson approximation also isn&#39;t terrible when <span class="tex">$N$</span> is as low as 10 as long as <span class="tex">$q$</span> is very small &#40;e.g.  <span class="tex">$&lt;0.05$</span> &#41;.</p>
<p>The fit remains poor when <span class="tex">$q &gt;&gt; 0.5$</span> and when <span class="tex">$N$</span> is small.</p>
</div>

<p>This visualization shows the aggregated posterior distribution across all of the trials and model points. The darker shaded band indicates the middle 50&#37; of the posterior:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>let
    f = Figure(resolution=(1280,960))
    a = Any # outer variable to set as axis for to grab legend
    
    for (i,N) in enumerate(reverse(Ns))
        ax = Axis(f[i+1,1:10],
        xticks=qs,
        ylabel="N=$N"
        )
        a = ax
        xlims!(0,1)
        model_idx = findall(x-&gt;x.N == N,model_points)

        for n in model_idx
            c = bpchains[n]
            q = model_points[n].q
            y = model_points[n].N
            bpoints = vcat([x.bc["q"][:] for x in c]...)
            ppoints = vcat([x.pc["q"][:] for x in c]...)
            @show bpoints
            bqtls = quantile(bpoints,[.25,.75])
            pqtls = quantile(ppoints,[.25,.75])
            j = density!(
                bpoints,
                linewidth=10,
                strokewidth = 1, 
                strokecolor = (:grey30,0.6),
                label="Binomial",
            	color=(:red,.25),
            )
            plot_band_under!(ax,j,0,bqtls[1],bqtls[2],"Binomial")
        

            j = density!(
                ppoints, 
                color=(:blue,.25),
                linewidth=10,
                strokewidth = 1, 
                strokecolor = (:grey30,0.6),
                label="Poisson",
            )
            plot_band_under!(ax,j,0,pqtls[1],pqtls[2],"Poisson")

            hideydecorations!(ax,label=false)
        end

        scatter!(
            qs,
            zeros(length(qs)),
            marker = :vline,
            markersize=20,
            color=:grey30,
            label="actual value"
            )
    end

    Legend(f[1,5],a,unique=true,orientation=:horizontal)
    f
end

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>function plot_band_under!(ax,plot,y,low,high,label="")
    function points(plot)
        pts = plot.plots[2].converted[1][]
        [p[1] for p in pts], [p[2] for p in pts]
    end    
    xs′, ys′ = points(plot)

    filt = findall(x-&gt; (x ≥ low) && (x ≤ high),xs′)
    b = band!(ax,xs′[filt], fill(y,length(filt)), ys′[filt], color=(plot.color, 0.9),transparency=true,shading = false,) # 0.25 alpha
    translate!(b,0,0,5)
end
